factor_name: "drawup_from_252d_low"
hypothesis: >
  Stocks deep into recovery from their 252-day low have sustained
  recency momentum that persists on 21-63 day horizons. This mirrors
  the rolling-drawdown factor but captures the POSITIVE side: distance
  traveled UP from the annual low is a proxy for accumulated investor
  conviction post-trough.
formula: >
  rolling_min = close.rolling(252).min()
  drawup = (close - rolling_min) / rolling_min
  cross-sectional z-score per date (uses .rolling() — past only)
required_fields: [close]
suitable_horizon: [21d, 63d]
suitable_universe: "全 universe"
suitable_regime: [BULL, RISK_ON, NEUTRAL]
expected_edge: "IC ~0.04-0.08 on 21d horizon in trending regimes"
expected_risk: "Late-stage bull market may see high drawup but low forward return (mean reversion dominates); fails in choppy/sideways markets"
possible_failure_modes:
  - "high correlation with 252d momentum (must check via dedup)"
  - "concentrated in a few winners — narrow breadth in strong bull"
  - "survivorship bias if universe is pruned post-drawdown"
novelty_vs_existing_factors: >
  max_dd_126d measures current drawdown from rolling HIGH (negative
  signal). drawdown_current uses peak-to-trough. No existing factor
  measures drawup from rolling LOW. Sign and path-shape of this
  feature differs from momentum factors even though both favor uptrends.
compute_fn_path: "research.llm_candidates.round_01.compute_fns:drawup_from_252d_low"
